covered: Valid Request: Scenarios cover standard successful GET with default, offset/limit, and audit parameter variations.
Empty Response: Scenario for no bundles ensures empty array handling (TC06).
Query Parameters: Multiple valid/invalid combinations covered (offset, limit, audit, extra params).
Authorization: Unauthorized access scenario (TC12) and valid auth handling across scenarios.
Error Handling: Scenarios for invalid pagination parameters (TC08, TC09), invalid audit (TC10), limit too large (TC11), and dependency/system failures (TC13).
Edge Cases: Negative offset/limit (TC08/TC09), positive overflow tests (TC16), and extra unexpected parameters (TC15).
Regression: Backward compatibility (TC20) and MINIMAL audit/offset regression (TC19).
Performance: Basic efficiency checks under normal load (TC17) and peak load (TC18).
Pagination Coverage: Multiple scenarios covering offset/limit behavior, zero data, and out-of-range values.
gaps: Caching and caching headers validation (ETag, Cache-Control) not tested.
Rate limiting/throttling behavior not explicitly tested (beyond performance scenarios).
Authorized access without authentication and permission scope nuances beyond 401/403 are not deeply explored.
Comprehensive large-dataset pagination correctness beyond first page (beyond TC02 with 150+ items) is not extensively validated.
Explicit 403 responses and permission-related audit exposure scenarios are not separately covered.
recommendations: Add tests to validate caching headers (ETag, Cache-Control) on responses.
Introduce rate limiting/throttling scenarios to verify behavior under high request volume.
Expand authorization tests to include 403 scenarios and token scope/permissions checks.
Add deeper pagination tests with very large datasets to confirm consistent offset/limit handling across multiple pages.
Consider explicit tests for boundary conditions on audit metadata retrieval across different pagination states.
